<subSubSection id="209E1AAD0D69B26BFF66FAFBFB861101" pageId="5" pageNumber="44" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="683B49260D69B26BFF66FAFBFB861101" blockId="5.[151,1437,1374,1905]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis id="5AF095340D69B26BFF66FAFBFE5D1229" bold="true" box="[151,428,1374,1401]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">Diagnosis and remarks</emphasis>
. 
<collectorName id="C5712CF00D69B26BFE48FAFAFE1A1229" box="[441,491,1375,1401]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">This</collectorName>
species was originally described as 
<taxonomicName id="AF8432A50D69B26BFC75FAFAFAF61229" authority="Fisher, 1953" authorityName="Fisher" authorityYear="1953" box="[900,1287,1374,1401]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Epimelitta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aureopilis">
<emphasis id="5AF095340D69B26BFC75FAFAFB801229" box="[900,1137,1375,1401]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">Epimelitta aureopilis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="0C1534D70D69B26BFB88FAFAFAF61229" author="Fisher, W. S." box="[1145,1287,1374,1401]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44" pagination="14 - 17" refId="ref4477" refString="Fisher, W. S. (1953) New Cerambycid beetles belonging to the tribe Rhinotragini (Coleoptera). The Pan-Pacific Entomologist, 29 (1), 14 - 17." type="journal article" year="1953">Fisher, 1953</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<collectorName id="C5712CF00D69B26BFAE3FAFAFAB51229" box="[1298,1348,1375,1401]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">This</collectorName>
species can be separated from congeners by the elytra shorter, extending to about base of abdominal segment I, broadly rounded apically; metatibiae with dense brush of suberect setae; and genae about 1/2 as long as lower eye lobe. 
<collectorName id="C5712CF00D69B26BFA74FA02FA6D1291" box="[1413,1436,1447,1473]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">In</collectorName>
male specimens examined, the eyes are narrowly separated in front by about 7 ommatidia, while in females they are widely separated by more than 20 ommatidia, or about 2/3 width of an eye lobe. 
<collectorName id="C5712CF00D69B26BFBE3FA4AFB291159" box="[1042,1240,1519,1545]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">Antennomeres VI</collectorName>
–XI of both sexes with small, indistinct sensory pores on dorsal and ventral surface of each antennomere (not reported in original description). 
<collectorName id="C5712CF00D69B26BFEE1F992FEB31101" box="[272,322,1591,1617]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">This</collectorName>
species was described from 
<specimenCount id="7E8282AF0D69B26BFD72F992FD2D1101" box="[643,732,1591,1617]" pageId="5" pageNumber="44" type="male">13 male</specimenCount>
specimens from 
<collectingCountry id="109309B60D69B26BFC6DF992FC031101" box="[924,1010,1591,1617]" name="Mexico" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">Mexico</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="AA4087C40D69B26BFBF0F992FB9D1101" box="[1025,1132,1591,1617]" country="Mexico" name="Veracruz de Ignacio de la Llave" pageId="5" pageNumber="44">Veracruz</collectingRegion>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
